## Migration: `TimedExecutor` â†’ .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement via `Thread.Abort`

### Why this breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` â€” it cannot forcibly kill threads. `Thread.ResetAbort()` and `ThreadAbortException` are also dead APIs.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(), timeout, CancellationToken.None);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage comparison

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ExpensiveWork(), 
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) â€” basic (same signature, drop-in)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ExpensiveWork(), 
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER â€” cooperative (preferred, work actually stops)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return finalResult;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Critical pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive** | The `Func<T>` overload (no token) won't actually stop running work â€” the task continues in the background. The caller gets the `TimeoutException`, but the thread keeps running. |
| **Always pass the token through** | If `work` calls other methods, forward the token to every async/blocking call. One missing link = cancellation stalls. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` ignores tokens** | Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` inside work with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `Task.Delay(ms, token)`. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer leaks. The `using` handles this. |
| **Uncooperative code (can't modify)** | If `work` calls code you don't control and it can't accept a token, the only true kill mechanism is `Process.Kill` on a child process. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`. |

### What was removed

| .NET Framework API | Replacement |
|---------------------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (via `CancelAfter`) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed â€” check `token.IsCancellationRequested` if you want to continue |
| `new Thread()` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run()` |

The key mental shift: **you are no longer killing threads â€” you are asking work to stop, and the work must listen.**
